SIMPLE: filiation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Filiation
<hw>Fil`i*a"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL.
<ets>filiatio</ets>, fr. L. <ets>filius</ets> son: cf. F.
<ets>filiation</ets>. See <er>Filial</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The
relationship of a son or child to a parent, esp. to a father.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The relation of paternity and <qex>filiation</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir M. Hale.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>The assignment of a bastard child
to some one as its father; affiliation.</def>
<rj><au>Smart.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Descent from, or as if from, a parent; relationship
like that of a son; <as>as, to determine the <ex>filiation</ex> of a
language</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>One that is derived from a parent or source; an
offshoot; <as>as, the <ex>filiations</ex> are from a common
stock</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Filibeg</ent>⟦br⟧
